{"parse":{"title":"Godless Painters","pageid":49364446,"revid":856147770,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Adam_and_Eve.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Adam_and_Eve.jpg/220px-Adam_and_Eve.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"319\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Adam_and_Eve.jpg/330px-Adam_and_Eve.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Adam_and_Eve.jpg/440px-Adam_and_Eve.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"688\" data-file-height=\"999\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Adam_and_Eve.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Sebald Beham, <i><a href=\"/wiki/Adam_and_Eve\" title=\"Adam and Eve\">Adam and Eve</a></i>, 1543, 82 x 56 mm.</div></div></div>  <div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Pencz_Lot_and_his_daughters.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Pencz_Lot_and_his_daughters.jpg/220px-Pencz_Lot_and_his_daughters.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"170\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Pencz_Lot_and_his_daughters.jpg/330px-Pencz_Lot_and_his_daughters.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Pencz_Lot_and_his_daughters.jpg/440px-Pencz_Lot_and_his_daughters.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1886\" data-file-height=\"1454\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Pencz_Lot_and_his_daughters.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>George Pencz, <i><a href=\"/wiki/Lot_(biblical_person)\" title=\"Lot (biblical person)\">Lot</a> and his daughters</i>, 1544.</div></div></div><p>\n\"<b>Godless painters</b>\" is a term used by art historians to refer to <a href=\"/wiki/Sebald_Beham\" title=\"Sebald Beham\">Sebald Beham</a>, his brother <a href=\"/wiki/Barthel_Beham\" title=\"Barthel Beham\">Barthel</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/George_Pencz\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"George Pencz\">George Pencz</a>, as exemplified in the title of a 2011 catalog of the Beham brothers' works, <i>The Godless Painters of Nuremberg:  Convention and Subversion in the Printmaking of the Beham Brothers</i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Die_gottlosen_Maler,_2011_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Die_gottlosen_Maler,_2011-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The epithet was coined in derision of the three painters during an inquest conducted by the <a href=\"/wiki/Lutheran\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Lutheran\">Lutheran</a> dominated city council of Nuremberg in 1525, which concerned the artists' <a href=\"/wiki/Protestant\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Protestant\">protestant</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Heterodoxy\" title=\"Heterodoxy\">heterodoxy</a>. The term is a <a href=\"/wiki/Double_entendre\" title=\"Double entendre\">double entendre</a> eluding more to the content of the \"godless painters\" works, rather than the doctrinal views for which they were condemned. The typically small-scale prints often depicted biblical or moral themes with a touch of <a href=\"/wiki/Eroticism\" title=\"Eroticism\">eroticism</a>. The \"godless painters\" are also considered to be leading representatives of the group of <a href=\"/wiki/Little_Masters\" title=\"Little Masters\">little masters</a>.</p><div class=\"thumb tleft\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:1540_Beham_Vanitas_anagoria.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/1540_Beham_Vanitas_anagoria.JPG/220px-1540_Beham_Vanitas_anagoria.JPG\" width=\"220\" height=\"284\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/1540_Beham_Vanitas_anagoria.JPG/330px-1540_Beham_Vanitas_anagoria.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/1540_Beham_Vanitas_anagoria.JPG/440px-1540_Beham_Vanitas_anagoria.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"3485\" data-file-height=\"4491\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:1540_Beham_Vanitas_anagoria.JPG\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Barthel Beham, <i>Vanity</i>, 1540, <a href=\"/wiki/Hamburger_Kunsthalle\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Hamburger Kunsthalle\">Hamburger Kunsthalle</a>.</div></div></div>\n<p>The inquest consisted of numerous interrogations concerning matters of <a href=\"/wiki/Baptism\" title=\"Baptism\">baptism</a>, the <a href=\"/wiki/Eucharist\" title=\"Eucharist\">Eucharist</a>, and the role of <a href=\"/wiki/Secular\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Secular\">secular</a> authorities. Imprisonment and torture were threatened, but ultimately the three were condemned to short-term exile from the city.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Stewart,_2015_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Stewart,_2015-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>The inquiries took place during the <a href=\"/wiki/German_Peasants%27_War\" title=\"German Peasants&#39; War\">German Peasants' War</a>, which involved theological controversies between <a href=\"/wiki/Martin_Luther\" title=\"Martin Luther\">Martin Luther</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Thomas_M%C3%BCntzer\" title=\"Thomas M\u00fcntzer\">Thomas M\u00fcntzer</a> on the matters at issues in the inquest into the beliefs of the painters. \n</p><p>Historical accounts regarding the painters have often been cursory, and sometimes confused due to the lack of availability of primary sources.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Stewart,_2015_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Stewart,_2015-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  The aforementioned catalog, <i>The Godless Painters of Nuremberg</i>, promises to correct this deficit.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Die_gottlosen_Maler,_2011_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Die_gottlosen_Maler,_2011-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Godless_Painters&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Die_gottlosen_Maler,_2011-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Die_gottlosen_Maler,_2011_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Die_gottlosen_Maler,_2011_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><i>Die gottlosen Maler von N\u00fcrnberg:  Konvention und Subversion in der Druckgrafik der Beham-Br\u00fcder</i>, edited by J\u00fcrgen M\u00fcller and Thomas Schauerte.  See <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.reimer-mann-verlag.de/controller.php?cmd=detail&amp;titelnummer=300040&amp;verlag=3\">book review</a>.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Stewart,_2015-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Stewart,_2015_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Stewart,_2015_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Alison G. Stewart, <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1025&amp;context=artfacpub\"><i>The Artist's Lament in 1528. Exile, Printing, and the Reformation</i></a>, 2015</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Alison G. Stewart, <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.jhna.org/index.php/past-issues/volume-4-issue-2/159-sebald-beham-entrepreneur-printmaker-painter-%7Cpublisher=Journal\"><i>Sebald Beham: Entrepreneur, Printmaker, Painter</i></a>, 2012</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Godless_Painters&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Vincent_Willem_van_Gogh_107.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60/Vincent_Willem_van_Gogh_107.jpg/24px-Vincent_Willem_van_Gogh_107.jpg\" width=\"24\" height=\"30\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60/Vincent_Willem_van_Gogh_107.jpg/37px-Vincent_Willem_van_Gogh_107.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60/Vincent_Willem_van_Gogh_107.jpg/49px-Vincent_Willem_van_Gogh_107.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1256\" data-file-height=\"1539\" /></a></td><td><i>This artist-related article is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help Wikipedia by <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Godless_Painters&amp;action=edit\">expanding it</a>.</i><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\" style=\"position: absolute; right: 15px; display: none;\"><ul><li class=\"nv-view\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template:Artist-stub\" title=\"Template:Artist-stub\"><abbr title=\"View this template\">v</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-talk\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template_talk:Artist-stub\" title=\"Template talk:Artist-stub\"><abbr title=\"Discuss this template\">t</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-edit\"><a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Artist-stub&amp;action=edit\"><abbr title=\"Edit this template\">e</abbr></a></l